116
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:30,840
Rym: Yes, five people.

117
00:06:31,642 --> 00:06:32,960
Rym: With Skype 2.0.

118
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:36,300
Scott: Right, with Skype 2.0, you can talk in a conversation with five people.

119
00:06:37,761 --> 00:06:47,019
Scott: If you have an Intel processor, as in a Pentium 4, or one of those core duo things, or an Intel processor, you can talk to ten people at once.

120
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:48,540
Rym: Ten people, eh?

121
00:06:48,820 --> 00:06:55,179
Scott: And if you have an AMD processor or any other company that's not Intel, you can only talk to five.

122
00:06:55,940 --> 00:07:05,999
Rym: Now, they claim that the reason they did this was simply because other chips that aren't Intel don't have the capability of handling ten conversations at the same time.

123
00:07:06,881 --> 00:07:10,760
Scott: As someone who knows a whole lot about technology and processors?

124
00:07:11,740 --> 00:07:11,976
Scott: Bullshit.

125
00:07:12,623 --> 00:07:15,700
Rym: Yeah, I think we need a little WAV file to signify bullshit.

126
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:27,300
Scott: There is no technological reason why a non-Intel processor cannot handle the processing necessary for a ten-person internet phone conversation.

127
00:07:27,780 --> 00:07:28,457
Scott: None whatsoever.

128
00:07:28,780 --> 00:07:37,319
Scott: The only reason is because, in the code of Skype, they wrote, "If processor equals Intel, then limit equals ten.

129
00:07:37,821 --> 00:07:40,176
Scott: If processor equals AMD, limit equals

130
00:07:40,236 --> 00:07:40,599
Scott: five.".

131
00:07:40,901 --> 00:07:42,799
Rym: Now, why would they do this, you might ask?

132
00:07:43,421 --> 00:07:43,838
Scott: Money money!

133
00:07:44,843 --> 00:07:45,034
Rym: Money!

134
00:07:45,301 --> 00:07:47,880
Rym: Yeah, Intel had a little deal going with them.

135
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:48,416
Rym: Little deal.

136
00:07:48,960 --> 00:07:51,692
Scott: So, AMD comes and says, "We got a subpoena,".

137
00:07:51,812 --> 00:07:57,800
Scott: and the subpoena says, "Show us your little dealie," so we can see if your little dealie is against the law.

138
00:07:58,200 --> 00:08:05,559
