00:12:46,588 --> 00:12:47,100
Scott: Oh, oh, okay.

207
00:12:47,281 --> 00:12:49,880
Rym: There's one that Superman's a dick, and there's all these other archives.

208
00:12:50,040 --> 00:12:51,078
Rym: The site is worth going to.

209
00:12:52,060 --> 00:12:58,459
Rym: The only other thing I learned from it was that, one, if ever in a Superman story, Red Kryptonite appears.

210
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:06,880
Rym: That just means they ran out of ideas, 'cause Red Kryptonite, like, splits Superman in two, or just makes crazy crap happen, so they have a plot.

211
00:13:08,181 --> 00:13:12,640
Scott: It's really hard to write stories about Superman, because Superman just wins every time.

212
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:13,133
Scott: It's just bleh.

213
00:13:13,661 --> 00:13:20,099
Scott: You have to write a story about something else, and then use Superman as your deus ex machina or something like that.

214
00:13:20,581 --> 00:13:22,079
Rym: That's really the only way to use it.

215
00:13:22,680 --> 00:13:26,359
Rym: It was Superman being controlled by giant bugs, and then everyone has to stop him.

216
00:13:27,445 --> 00:13:28,620
Rym: That happened at least twice.

217
00:13:29,140 --> 00:13:31,700
Scott: Why is he so prone to giant bug control?

218
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:32,275
Rym: You know why?

219
00:13:32,400 --> 00:13:33,720
Rym: 'Cause he's a giant asshole.

220
00:13:34,662 --> 00:13:35,819
Rym: He's not that smart, either.

221
00:13:36,602 --> 00:13:37,799
Scott: No, he really isn't that smart.

222
00:13:38,040 --> 00:13:47,160
Scott: You'd think being, you know-- 'cause that's the problem, is all the Superman stories still take place within, like, the first human life length of his life.

223
00:13:47,681 --> 00:13:50,416
Scott: If you, like, waited around 'til Superman was, like, 300, he'd be smarter.

224
00:13:51,640 --> 00:13:51,877
Scott: You know?

225
00:13:52,343 --> 00:13:52,999
Rym: No, he'd be dead.

226
00:13:53,120 --> 00:13:54,100
Rym: You know, Kryptonite and all.

227
00:13:54,780 --> 00:13:57,440
Scott: I thought he lives-- he's immortal, unless Kryptonite comes around.

228
00:13:57,520 --> 00:13:58,539
Rym: Yeah, so I'll just Kryptonite him.

229
00:13:59,222 --> 00:14:00,040
Scott: That doesn't seem to work.

230
00:14:00,140 --> 00:14:01,879
Scott: It's happened a bunch of times, and he always seems to win.

231
00:14:02,424 --> 00:14:02,857
Rym: You know why?

232
00:14:03,162 --> 00:14:04,500
Scott: I don't think he's gonna fall for it anymore.

233
00:14:04,560 --> 00:14:09,079
Rym: Because the people who write it wouldn't kill him, because that's the end of their revenue stream.

234
00:14:09,821 --> 00:14:12,059
Scott: Yeah, I'm gonna talk about that in a few minutes.

235
00:14:12,301 --> 00:14:15,477
Rym: Yeah, I only brought this site up, 'cause it's been around for a while, but today--.

236
00:14:15,980 --> 00:14:19,000
Rym: well, usually we use it today to talk about anime and a little bit of comics.

237
00:14:19,520 --> 00:14:23,800
Rym: Today, we're going mad comics and a tiny bit of anime.

238
00:14:24,640 --> 00:14:24,712
Scott: Yep.

239
00:14:26,100 --> 00:14:27,700
Rym: So, anyway, on to the comics.

240
00:14:28,661 --> 00:14:31,680
Scott: So, if you did-- first, I wanna talk about the New York Comic-Con.

241
00:14:32,927 --> 00:14:33,540
Scott: It was bad.

242
00:14:34,603 --> 00:14:36,559
Rym: Uh, uh, debacle comes to mind.

243
00:14:36,983 --> 00:14:39,060
Scott: I like to use the-- I like to say debacle.

244
00:14:40,062 --> 00:14:40,519
Rym: Uh, clusterfuck.

245
00:14:41,360 --> 00:14:43,599
Scott: Alright, now, a lot of people have said a lot of things.

246
00:14:44,340 --> 00:14:52,780
Scott: The first thing a lot of people point out is that what was going on in the con, as in the things happening there that were supposed to happen, were actually quite good.

247
00:14:53,561 --> 00:14:58,820
Scott: And while I did not experience them, despite my attempt to do so, I really can't disagree.

248
00:14:59,140 --> 00:15:05,900
Scott: I mean, you know, the list of just people that were there, if you're into-- you know, if you know who these people are, is quite astounding.

249
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:12,559
Rym: Now, I have a counterpoint to that, in that, according to people who were there, there were all those panels, and they all looked kinda good, right?

250
00:15:13,520 --> 00:15:23,698
Rym: Apparently, despite the fact that the exhibit area was so full of people, the state police were turning people away, almost no one went to panels, and even the panels that happened were mostly empty rooms.

251
00:15:24,340 --> 00:15:30,640
Scott: Well, the problem is, some panels that people cared about were just full up, because people were trying to escape the crowded exhibit room.

252
00:15:30,820 --> 00:15:35,539
Scott: Yeah, but every other panel-- The panels that no one cared about, no one went to, because they didn't want to get stuck out.

253
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:42,300
Rym: Yeah, then there were the panels where people couldn't go to them, because the people who were doing them were turned away by security.

254
00:15:42,820 --> 00:15:51,999
Scott: Yup, Douglas Rushkoff, one of the guys I wanted to see there, who I didn't get to see, because I didn't get in, which I'll tell you about, he actually couldn't get to one of his signings, because he got stuck out.

255
00:15:52,401 --> 00:15:54,880
Scott: And he was a guest, an official guest of the con.

256
00:15:55,320 --> 00:15:59,258
Rym: So maybe before you talk about what was going to happen at the con, did you talk about what happened at the con?

257
00:15:59,761 --> 00:16:03,100
Scott: So I arrive at this con, and it's a comic con in the Javits Center.

258
00:16:03,301 --> 00:16:13,680
Rym: Now, I was going to go, and the only reason I didn't was that I actually got sick at Katsu Con, and all last week, I was fairly ill and full of NyQuil while I was doing the show.

259
00:16:14,560 --> 00:16:20,033
Rym: So Saturday morning, I wake up around 8 to catch the train with Scott, and I didn't feel like going.

260
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:21,299
Rym: I just rolled over and went to bed.

261
00:16:22,640 --> 00:16:27,779
Rym: Our friend Scott Johnson, who was also going to go, was also sick, also from Katsu Con, so he didn't go either.

262
00:16:28,260 --> 00:16:34,059
Rym: So I know I talked Katsu Con up for being awesome, it gets one more point of awesome for saving me from the New York Comic Con.

263
00:16:34,300 --> 00:16:34,797
Scott: Yup, luck.

264
00:16:35,161 --> 00:16:35,718
Scott: Luck be you.

265
00:16:36,340 --> 00:16:42,100
Scott: So I get there, and if you've ever been to the Javits Center, it's not like other convention centers.

266
00:16:43,021 --> 00:16:47,660
Scott: It's a main hall on the first floor, and first of all, the lobby is huge.

267
00:16:48,020 --> 00:16:50,960
Scott: Lobby could be an entire convention room, but it's not, it's just a lobby.

268
00:16:51,500 --> 00:16:57,959
Scott: But it's actually good, because a lot of convention centers don't have big enough lobbies, and this one can pretty much handle anything you throw at it.

269
00:16:58,241 --> 00:17:06,680
Scott: It's an invincible lobby, with a coat check in the basement, and plenty of room for registration lines and booths, and all kinds of stuff.

270
00:17:06,780 --> 00:17:11,359
Scott: There's even like a whole food court up there, with actually somewhat decently priced food.

271
00:17:11,520 --> 00:17:13,539
Rym: The Javits is where the New York Auto Show is.

272
00:17:14,286 --> 00:17:14,900
Rym: The Javits is enormous.

273
00:17:14,900 --> 00:17:18,338
Scott: The Javits is where every convention in New York is, because it's the only place you can put one.

274
00:17:18,681 --> 00:17:19,880
Scott: There is no other convention center.

275
00:17:19,940 --> 00:17:25,900
Rym: Now the Javits has a lot of problems, in that it's on the west side of Manhattan, all alone.

276
00:17:26,481 --> 00:17:28,019
Scott: It's hard to get to it by subway.

277
00:17:28,140 --> 00:17:30,400
Scott: You have to take a taxi, or a bus, or your feet.

278
00:17:30,620 --> 00:17:32,511
Rym: Yeah, there are only two buses that I know of.

279
00:17:32,551 --> 00:17:34,120
Rym: that go to it, and they're real inconvenient.

280
00:17:34,620 --> 00:17:35,740
Rym: The subway doesn't go to it.

281
00:17:35,820 --> 00:17:38,840
Scott: There are a couple shuttles that go there, but it's not worth it.

282
00:17:38,840 --> 00:17:40,000
Scott: You're better off just walking.

283
00:17:40,120 --> 00:17:43,080
Scott: Get a subway as close as you can, which is probably like Penn Station, and walk.

284
00:17:44,462 --> 00:17:46,820
Scott: Or take a taxi if you got money, or if you're in a rush.

285
00:17:47,180 --> 00:17:47,395
Scott: Whatever.

286
00:17:48,120 --> 00:17:49,780
Scott: So you go into the Javits, it's a giant lobby.

287
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:54,740
Scott: On the main floor, there are three giant rooms, which is the main convention area.

288
00:17:54,822 --> 00:17:55,638
Scott: This place is huge.

289
00:17:55,980 --> 00:18:00,780
Scott: These are like super high ceilings, super large in square footage rooms.

290
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:04,540
Scott: We're talking tremendous football field, many times rooms.

291
00:18:05,400 --> 00:18:08,640
Scott: And usually when there's a convention, they take all three of those rooms combined.

292
00:18:08,860 --> 00:18:13,260
Scott: Very rarely do they split up those rooms, but they can, and they have in the past.

293
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:15,098
Scott: But usually it's one big room.

294
00:18:16,360 --> 00:18:23,680
Scott: Upstairs there's like this T-shaped room, and it's pretty small, relative, but it's not small overall.

295
00:18:24,582 --> 00:18:27,820
Scott: And, you know, usually cons will use that as an auxiliary room.

296
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:34,699
Scott: And downstairs, there is the downstairs hall, which is just a convention hall, and it's the downstairs hall.

297
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:40,637
Scott: It's not as big as the main hall, it's just for little cons and things like that, you know, like a little tiny trade show, something like that.

298
00:18:41,600 --> 00:18:48,218
Scott: So I get there, and I fully expect the con to be taking up all three of the main, you know, the giant giant rooms.

299
00:18:49,200 --> 00:18:53,160
Scott: Much to my amazement, it is in the downstairs little tiny convention hall.

300
00:18:53,462 --> 00:18:55,900
Scott: And I said, "Uh oh, that's not right.

301
00:18:56,601 --> 00:18:57,830
Scott: It's going to be mighty cramped in

302
00:18:57,850 --> 00:18:58,052
Scott: there.".

303
00:18:59,302 --> 00:19:00,638
Scott: Then I saw something else.

304
00:19:01,340 --> 00:19:07,668
Scott: Not only was it in the downstairs convention hall, it was one half of the downstairs convention hall.

305
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:11,159
Scott: The other half of it was occupied by a travel show.

306
00:19:11,980 --> 00:19:12,087
Rym: Great.

307
00:19:13,120 --> 00:19:18,159
Scott: So, there was a line going out the door, but the line didn't intimidate me, because I've been in longer lines than that.

308
00:19:18,260 --> 00:19:22,220
Scott: This thing was like, this is a wuss line compared to lines I've been in.

309
00:19:22,320 --> 00:19:31,080
Rym: The line for the concert, the Lark concert at Otakon two years ago, that went like down the street around several blocks, and then just off into the distance.

310
00:19:31,120 --> 00:19:32,300
Scott: Yeah, this is a wuss line.

311
00:19:32,540 --> 00:19:35,460
Scott: I mean, this thing was around only one corner of a building.

312
00:19:35,560 --> 00:19:39,680
Scott: It was maybe less than one football field length out the door of the Javits.

313
00:19:40,100 --> 00:19:45,337
Scott: So I just got into it like, doo doo doo doo doo doo doo, you know, patiently, got pretty close to the building too.

314
00:19:46,342 --> 00:20:03,020
Scott: You know, and there was stuff going on the line, a lot of people coming, walking back and forth up and down the line peddling stuff, you know, trying to sell their crap, give you their free little card with a coupon on it or something, or inviting you to go to a museum that has a comics exhibit, you know, all kinds of shit.

315
00:20:03,720 --> 00:20:05,200
Scott: A bunch of nerds hanging out in line.

316
00:20:05,580 --> 00:20:09,440
Scott: Surprisingly for a comic convention, I only saw like a couple Spider-Man type things.

317
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:14,889
Scott: It seemed like the comic nerds might have like a t-shirt with a Superman or a Spider-Man on it.

318
00:20:15,700 --> 00:20:19,680
Scott: And I saw more Naruto headbands than I saw anything else.

319
00:20:20,080 --> 00:20:26,460
Rym: Well it seems to me that, I mean, there is this comic culture, but anime fans are the ones that have the conventions.

320
00:20:27,722 --> 00:20:29,920
Rym: So anime fans are in that convention mindset.

321
00:20:30,500 --> 00:20:36,720
Rym: So all the anime fans in New York City just came to this for a day, you know, they just came out of the woodwork, and they're numerous.

322
00:20:37,240 --> 00:20:44,059
Scott: It's just weird that the percentage of freaky type of action going on in the convention line was much less than what I was used to.

323
00:20:44,562 --> 00:20:48,820
Scott: So the line itself was pretty boring compared to what convention lines usually are.

324
00:20:49,020 --> 00:20:53,220
Scott: Like I couldn't really get a conversation going on with anyone or make any friends in the line.

325
00:20:53,300 --> 00:20:54,399
Scott: They were all just kind of bleh.

326
00:20:55,240 --> 00:20:56,954
Scott: You know, I was like, "Oh, so

327
00:20:56,974 --> 00:20:57,458
Scott: what?".

328
00:20:57,801 --> 00:20:58,972
Scott: And the people were just like, "Yeah,

329
00:20:59,113 --> 00:20:59,497
Scott: whatever.".

330
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:06,459
Rym: Wow, god, I mean even when we went to New York City to see Miyamoto, we just- No, because those are Nintendo kids, you can talk to them.

331
00:21:06,660 --> 00:21:11,678
Rym: Yeah, but anime kids we can talk to, gamers, we went to UberCon, everyone we met we just hung out with.

332
00:21:12,383 --> 00:21:25,800
Scott: I think it was just the people I was near in line, because I knew a lot of- there were a lot of people I know on the inside of the con I could have talked to, because I kind of know them from online and stuff, so I probably could have gotten good stuff from them, but in the line I was in, everyone was bleh.

333
00:21:26,020 --> 00:21:35,320
Scott: So then all of a sudden, this guy comes down the line with a megaphone, and he says, "We are not selling tickets anymore, we're sold out for today, go home, we have too many people.

334
00:21:36,381 --> 00:21:42,774
Scott: Unless you-" he says, "If you pre-ordered online, you know, if you already paid for your tickets, you can go and get in, otherwise, go

335
00:21:42,794 --> 00:21:43,297
Scott: home.".

336
00:21:43,860 --> 00:21:49,780
Rym: Now, if that had been where it ended, if they just sold out and they couldn't sell any more tickets, that would have been fantastic.

337
00:21:50,201 --> 00:21:52,997
Rym: That would have been a huge success, they would have known to get a bigger venue next year.

338
00:21:53,540 --> 00:21:53,610
Scott: Yup.

339
00:21:54,321 --> 00:22:00,340
Rym: The second part of his statement, where people who had already bought their tickets are guaranteed in, was a filthy lie.

340
00:22:01,160 --> 00:22:05,320
Scott: Yup, there were people who had pre-registered who were just not able to get into the convention.

341
00:22:05,600 --> 00:22:09,096
Scott: Even people who had tickets, VIP tickets, which cost $100, right?

342
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:15,319
Rym: State troopers came and made sure no one got in, the fire marshal could have just shut the whole thing down.

343
00:22:15,580 --> 00:22:37,519
Scott: Yeah, basically what was happening is, because the room was full to the max, they would like let 25 people out, and then let 25 people in, and let people out, and let people in, and the going was really slow, and even if you had, like, even people who were professionals who were supposed to, like, the president of DC Comics couldn't get in, because he had to wait for other people to get out.

344
00:22:38,281 --> 00:22:41,100
Scott: So no matter what your ticket status, you couldn't get into the thing.

345
00:22:41,500 --> 00:22:43,980
Rym: And people who were in realized this and wouldn't leave.

346
00:22:44,440 --> 00:22:48,274
Scott: Yup, people who were in wouldn't leave because it would take them up to two hours to get back in.

347
00:22:49,301 --> 00:22:55,934
Scott: So, people were pretty much staying in this thing as long as they could, before leaving, and not only that, while they were in there, it was so crowded.

348
00:22:55,975 --> 00:23:00,480
Scott: you couldn't really stop and do stuff, because you would block the way immediately, it was so crowded.

349
00:23:00,880 --> 00:23:07,273
Rym: Not only all that, but Scott calls me from the city to tell me, "Oh, it's terrible, you're lucky you didn't come, I can't get in, it's a

350
00:23:07,313 --> 00:23:07,534
Rym: mess.".

351
00:23:08,400 --> 00:23:18,680
Rym: And then, you know, I was asleep in bed still at this point, so I wake up, I look online, I figure, alright, I'll go to the New York Comic-Con website, see what official announcement they've posted about the situation.

352
00:23:19,841 --> 00:23:21,820
Rym: They didn't even touch their website.

353
00:23:22,020 --> 00:23:28,300
Rym: In fact, they were still selling tickets online to the event for most of Saturday.

354
00:23:29,121 --> 00:23:36,160
Rym: I went through the entire process up until accepting the actual charge to my credit card, just to see if I could buy a ticket, and I could.

355
00:23:36,880 --> 00:23:40,218
Scott: They didn't stop selling tickets, I don't know if that actually would have gotten you a ticket.

356
00:23:40,600 --> 00:23:50,738
Rym: Oh, it would have, because they actually took the ticket system down later, and they put up a thing saying, "Don't buy tickets, if you bought one, we'll contact you," or something to that effect.

357
00:23:51,140 --> 00:24:08,319
Scott: Their policy, technically, was we don't have to give you a refund if we don't want to, but actually, they did make amends and give a lot of people their money back, and they did-- They, "Alright, tell you what, we'll guarantee that you can come in tomorrow on Sunday,".

358
00:24:08,721 --> 00:24:12,500
Rym: way out, and most people were so pissed they wouldn't take that, they wanted their money.

359
00:24:12,880 --> 00:24:13,041
Rym: Yeah,

360
00:24:13,723 --> 00:24:28,265
Scott: and the other thing is, I think they were talking about giving people special guest status at next year's New York Comic-Con, which I think they're going to change-- They had a big poster that said, "New York Comic-Con, the next time, will be these dates in the same place,".

361
00:24:28,345 --> 00:24:31,919
Scott: but I have a feeling they're going to change the date to get the bigger convention hall.

362
00:24:32,482 --> 00:24:33,820
Scott: At least one of the thirds of it.

363
00:24:33,920 --> 00:24:37,000
Scott: One of the thirds of it would have been sufficient, I think, for this size con.

364
00:24:37,520 --> 00:24:39,200
Scott: Two thirds of it would have been perfect.

365
00:24:39,782 --> 00:24:41,439
Scott: All three of them, maybe a little too big.

366
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,820
Rym: Now, this really bothers me, just in the sense that it's so unprofessional.

367
00:24:46,740 --> 00:24:50,580
Rym: I mean, this was a big convention, a real convention, there was a lot of money involved.

368
00:24:50,780 --> 00:24:50,867
Rym: Huge.

369
00:24:51,260 --> 00:24:54,499
Rym: It was at the Javits in New York City, it's the first one.

370
00:24:55,120 --> 00:25:07,420
Rym: Now I would have assumed, because even the crappest tiny anime con has a contingency plan for what if too many people show up, or what if not enough people show up.

371
00:25:07,720 --> 00:25:10,479
Rym: Just contingency plans in case a disaster happens.

372
00:25:11,341 --> 00:25:12,140
Rym: This con had nothing.

373
00:25:12,860 --> 00:25:18,140
Rym: Not only did they not expect these people, which is understandable, but they had no way to deal with it whatsoever.

374
00:25:20,221 --> 00:25:26,720
Rym: And these people, I mean, I don't even know what I can say other than that I'm really disappointed in almost everyone involved.

375
00:25:27,721 --> 00:25:34,840
Scott: Well, what it comes down to is this, when you run a convention, you have to know the number of people you can fit in the space you have.

376
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:37,957
Scott: You know, if you take out a restaurant, it says on the wall 200 people.

377
00:25:39,181 --> 00:25:42,459
Scott: So you know you don't let 200 people in, or more than 200 people in.

378
00:25:43,401 --> 00:25:47,814
Scott: They knew, they should have known, how many people they could have fit into the room they had.

379
00:25:48,020 --> 00:25:48,959
Rym: Yeah, Otakon knows.

380
00:25:49,560 --> 00:25:50,259
Rym: Katsukon knew.

381
00:25:50,660 --> 00:25:50,833
Rym: Yup.

382
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:54,380
Scott: So they knew how many pre-sales they had online.

383
00:25:54,681 --> 00:26:12,459
Scott: And I agree that based on the number of pre-sales, pre-orders, pre-regis, whatever you wanna call them, they had, that, you know, the average number for conventions, comic conventions, the number of registrations they would have had on-site would have been well below the limit of the number of people they could fit.

384
00:26:13,760 --> 00:26:22,459
Scott: However, when the time came, the number of on-site registrations was well beyond what they ever expected or could handle.

385
00:26:22,843 --> 00:26:24,839
Scott: Yet, that would have been fine too.

386
00:26:25,422 --> 00:26:27,120
Scott: You know, you didn't expect it, it happened.

387
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:28,620
Rym: But they kept selling them.

388
00:26:28,740 --> 00:26:35,299
Scott: They kept selling on-site registrations to the point where they exceeded the limit of the number of people who could be in there.

389
00:26:36,623 --> 00:26:37,739
Rym: This is just inexcusable.

390
00:26:39,382 --> 00:26:45,336
