468
00:34:09,681 --> 00:34:11,600
Scott: It's the way they're distributed in North America.

469
00:34:12,041 --> 00:34:18,659
Rym: And to put it in a nutshell, for anyone who doesn't want to listen to the whole episode, it's done in an archaic, terrible, backward-.

470
00:34:18,782 --> 00:34:19,699
Scott: No, it's not archaic.

471
00:34:20,002 --> 00:34:20,619
Scott: It just sucks.

472
00:34:21,179 --> 00:34:25,696
Scott: In fact, it's quite new, and that's why it sucks, is 'cause it goes away from the old good way.

473
00:34:25,880 --> 00:34:33,540
Rym: Well, I guess the distribution isn't archaic, but the way people find out about new comics is- It's not ar- no, 'cause the archaic implies that it's old.

474
00:34:34,040 --> 00:34:35,770
Scott: It's actually a very new way of doing it.

475
00:34:35,831 --> 00:34:37,158
Scott: that is less than 20 years old.

476
00:34:37,560 --> 00:34:38,360
Rym: I'm talking about the medium.

477
00:34:38,500 --> 00:34:40,799
Rym: I'm holding a piece of paper- Oh, yeah.

478
00:34:41,100 --> 00:34:41,565
Rym: -bound together.

479
00:34:41,605 --> 00:34:43,639
Rym: that tells me when things come out- That's archaic.

480
00:34:43,760 --> 00:34:46,300
Rym: -as opposed to looking on the internet and just, or, you know, yeah.

481
00:34:46,581 --> 00:34:48,179
Scott: Well, here, let me start from the beginning.

482
00:34:49,380 --> 00:34:56,418
Scott: In before the early '80s, so before we were alive, comic books in America were distributed the same way magazines were.

483
00:34:57,040 --> 00:34:59,240
Scott: You know, it's a periodical distribution company.

484
00:34:59,400 --> 00:35:03,580
Scott: Now, the way this works is, let's say you're a store, and you want to sell magazines.

485
00:35:04,582 --> 00:35:06,620
Scott: You don't really care which magazines you sell.

486
00:35:06,760 --> 00:35:10,777
Scott: I mean, you can pick and choose, because you know some will sell better than others, but that's up to you.

487
00:35:11,220 --> 00:35:14,555
Rym: Yeah, some stores don't want to- like, Walmart doesn't want to sell pornography, things like that.

488
00:35:14,944 --> 00:35:15,092
Rym: Mm-hmm.

489
00:35:15,700 --> 00:35:19,978
Scott: And you pick which magazines you want, and how many issues of each one you want, and you pay a price.

490
00:35:20,680 --> 00:35:25,020
Scott: They deliver those magazines to you on a monthly basis, because they're monthly magazines.

491
00:35:25,160 --> 00:35:30,759
Scott: Of course, you know, different magazines ship different weeks, so you actually get shipments like weekly when new magazines come out.

492
00:35:31,620 --> 00:35:35,619
Scott: But you know, you get them, and if you don't sell them, you're allowed to return them.

493
00:35:36,181 --> 00:35:38,220
Scott: And that's why magazines are kind of expensive, you know?

494
00:35:38,280 --> 00:35:45,100
Scott: You go to the store, and if you want to buy, like, you know, a big video game magazine, it can cost you, like, five, six bucks.

495
00:35:45,340 --> 00:35:45,919
Scott: They're not cheap.

496
00:35:46,280 --> 00:36:01,339
Rym: Now, the reason that magazines are often sold that way is mostly that it doesn't cost the magazine people as much to print it, and they usually expect that a bunch of them are going to come back, but they want the stores to display the magazine, even if the store doesn't think it'll sell.

497
00:36:01,841 --> 00:36:04,040
Rym: That way, it's basically advertising for the magazine.

498
00:36:04,440 --> 00:36:22,419
Scott: Yeah, magazines make their money on the ads and things, so their idea is to just increase readership, and the way this works is this is how you get those stores that sell a million magazines, 'cause you can do, you know, a small magazine can sell if it just gets shelf space.

499
00:36:22,880 --> 00:36:29,660
Scott: And if stores can return magazines they don't sell, they'll buy copies of freaking everything, because what do they care?

500
00:36:29,720 --> 00:36:30,279
Scott: They'll return it.

501
00:36:30,560 --> 00:36:36,456
Rym: Now, that business model, for anyone who remembers, is what almost killed TSR back in the D&D days.

502
00:36:36,790 --> 00:36:36,999
Scott: Yup.

503
00:36:37,100 --> 00:36:47,660
Rym: Because TSR had the same thing with all their Dungeons & Dragons books, and Dungeons & Dragons at one point tanked, and stores were sending them back by the truckload, and TSR almost went bankrupt.

504
00:36:48,362 --> 00:36:48,430
Scott: Yup.

505
00:36:49,281 --> 00:36:51,631
Scott: So, that's also how books, I think, are sold.

506
00:36:51,671 --> 00:36:58,519
Scott: in normal books, like at Borders and things, is, you know, if they buy paperback books and they don't want 'em, they can send 'em back for a return.

507
00:36:59,620 --> 00:37:03,919
Scott: Actually, a trade paperback, which is, you know, those big books full of comics...

508
00:37:04,221 --> 00:37:06,139
Rym: Yeah, I didn't actually know this until Scott told me.

509
00:37:06,200 --> 00:37:10,780
Scott: They're called trade paperbacks because you can't send 'em back, you know, they stay there.

510
00:37:11,240 --> 00:37:14,020
Scott: And they're all, trade also means it's like a weird shape and a weird size.

511
00:37:14,501 --> 00:37:17,520
Scott: It's all publishing terms that I've learned by doing a little bit of research.

512
00:37:18,160 --> 00:37:23,220
Scott: Now, in the early 80s, the comic books weren't selling so well, and they needed more money.

513
00:37:24,060 --> 00:37:34,260
Scott: So, this guy, his name is Phil Seuling, S-E-U-L-I-N-G, he was a convention organizer, actually, a Comic-Con convention organizer.

514
00:37:35,506 --> 00:37:36,359
Scott: He said, "You know what?

515
00:37:37,221 --> 00:37:39,798
Scott: Um, we're not selling so well on newsstands.

516
00:37:40,500 --> 00:37:42,953
Scott: Let me find a way to get comics to be more

517
00:37:42,973 --> 00:37:43,415
Scott: profitable.".

518
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:56,020
Scott: His idea was that instead of, you know, distributing through the periodical market, you know, distributors, that you, if you wanted to sell comics, you would buy them directly from the publisher.

519
00:37:56,100 --> 00:37:57,732
Scott: So you would say, "Marvel Comics, give me some

520
00:37:57,752 --> 00:37:58,397
Scott: Spider-Mans!".

521
00:37:59,322 --> 00:38:06,220
Scott: The way this worked is, well, you got a huge discount because you bought 'em, there were no middlemen between you and the publisher.

522
00:38:06,640 --> 00:38:08,540
Scott: No one was jacking up the price to make a profit.

523
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:12,440
Scott: You also got a huge discount because you couldn't return them.

524
00:38:12,720 --> 00:38:14,179
Scott: You bought it, you sold it.

525
00:38:14,380 --> 00:38:16,799
Scott: Or you bought it, it was for you, and you read it, you know?

526
00:38:17,341 --> 00:38:24,077
Rym: Now most people, like when I hear the word trade paperback, I just think, "Alright, that's the real book format of comic as opposed to the crappy comic format of

527
00:38:24,118 --> 00:38:24,379
Rym: comic.".

528
00:38:24,842 --> 00:38:26,739
Rym: And I just never put any thought into it beyond that.

529
00:38:27,180 --> 00:38:31,900
Scott: Right, so, this is what they did in the early 80s, is they switched to this direct delivery?

530
00:38:32,021 --> 00:38:35,580
Scott: where you want comic, you wanna sell comics, you have to buy them direct from the publisher.

531
00:38:36,820 --> 00:38:52,818
Scott: The problem with this is that now you couldn't get comics so easily in the newsstands and all kinds of places because those places weren't about to buy comic books and try to sell them and not be able to return them.

532
00:38:53,540 --> 00:38:55,759
Scott: You know, why, they're not gonna stock something they can't return.

533
00:38:56,340 --> 00:39:00,000
Scott: So the places to buy comic books were reduced to comic shops.

534
00:39:00,761 --> 00:39:04,920
Scott: But the price of comics went down and the profitability was maintained.

535
00:39:06,561 --> 00:39:21,239
Scott: That was until the 90s where they screwed up by, you know, what happened was they, the comic book stores, because there was a flood of speculation, people buying comics just to make money off of them, and of course those people never made money off of them.

536
00:39:21,901 --> 00:39:26,020
Scott: So they were shipping way too many, people were buying way too many copies of comics.

537
00:39:26,241 --> 00:39:30,180
Rym: This is the era of when, like, two characters would get married or a character would die.

538
00:39:30,780 --> 00:39:34,099
Scott: So they'd-- And they'd put holograms on the cover of the comic books and have two different covers.

539
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:45,973
Rym: They'd issue the same comic book in, like, it had four different covers, and each one would be a different hologram, and collectors would buy, like, eight copies of each one and put them each in their sealed bags and never touch them, hoping to sell them someday for a lot of

540
00:39:46,014 --> 00:39:46,179
Scott: money.

541
00:39:46,260 --> 00:40:06,998
Scott: Now there's still a little bit of that today, but this is, like, the time when it was an epidemic, is they would send way too many copies of every comic to the store, and eventually they didn't sell them all, and no one could return them, so the comic book store went out of business, comic book stores went out of business, the comic book companies have no one else to sell comic books to, uh oh.

542
00:40:07,980 --> 00:40:10,920
Scott: And that was when the 90s comic books pretty went downhill.

543
00:40:11,960 --> 00:40:14,980
Scott: Then came along this company, Diamond Comic Distributors.

544
00:40:15,780 --> 00:40:19,360
Scott: Diamond Comic Distributors is a direct distributor.

545
00:40:19,660 --> 00:40:24,178
Scott: What they do is, it's the same old model that they switched to in the early 80s.

546
00:40:25,062 --> 00:40:29,260
Scott: You know, you buy direct from the publishers, you can't return them, it's really cheap.

547
00:40:30,500 --> 00:40:40,000
Scott: What they do is, they bought, just kind of like Microsoft, they bought every other direct distributor, or the other direct distributors went out of business.

548
00:40:40,660 --> 00:40:48,080
Scott: So if you want a Marvel or DC comic, the only way to get them for your store is directly distributed through this company, Diamond Distributors.

549
00:40:48,867 --> 00:40:49,178
Scott: That's it.

550
00:40:49,380 --> 00:40:51,619
Scott: You can't get them like magazines, you can't, it's it.

551
00:40:52,162 --> 00:40:52,936
Scott: Only one thing.

552
00:40:55,101 --> 00:41:02,760
Scott: Tokyo Pop on the other hand, or Viz, or any of those manga distributors, you know, or manga publishers, they distribute through Diamond also.

553
00:41:03,661 --> 00:41:10,740
Scott: But they also distribute through the periodical distributors and the book store distributors and all kinds of other things, 'cause they don't have an exclusive agreement.

554
00:41:11,500 --> 00:41:14,900
Scott: But Marvel and DC comics sell only through Diamond Distributors.

555
00:41:16,421 --> 00:41:41,940
Scott: So, Diamond Distributors is a company that, because they can give you such a discount, and because things can't be returned, and because the things that they sell are sold in comic book stores, where they know that it's pretty much a place that nerds go to to buy things, they have the ability to sell really crazy, specialized stuff.

556
00:41:43,920 --> 00:41:57,059
Scott: And the way it works is they have a catalog that they put out every month that lists every single thing that they are going to distribute to comic book stores two months from now.

557
00:41:57,720 --> 00:42:05,320
Rym: So the March issue of this catalog is in my hands right now, I've been flipping through it while Scott's been talking.

558
00:42:05,520 --> 00:42:07,860
Scott: We'll tell you what's going to come out in May.

559
00:42:08,580 --> 00:42:10,560
Rym: Because apparently these people have never heard of the internet.

560
00:42:11,480 --> 00:42:15,596
