735
00:54:07,041 --> 00:54:13,940
Rym: You know-- I could see that if I was like-- say I read, I don't know, Rockato, and I liked it a lot.

736
00:54:14,821 --> 00:54:18,260
Rym: Maybe I might want to pre-order more, 'cause I already know I like it.

737
00:54:18,340 --> 00:54:19,260
Rym: That way I don't have to worry about it.

738
00:54:19,260 --> 00:54:19,736
Rym: I'll just get it.

739
00:54:20,020 --> 00:54:30,720
Scott: Yeah, and the way a subscription or a pre-order usually works is you say what you want, and they automatically-- they keep a list of your name and what you want, and whenever something you want comes into the store, they put it in a little folder.

740
00:54:30,880 --> 00:54:33,620
Scott: And then when you come into the store, you go to your folder and you empty it out.

741
00:54:33,820 --> 00:54:35,178
Scott: And you take all your stuff and you buy it.

742
00:54:35,660 --> 00:54:38,060
Scott: But you're sort of obligated to buy it if they put it in the folder.

743
00:54:38,482 --> 00:54:38,660
Scott: You know?

744
00:54:38,740 --> 00:54:44,320
Scott: It depends on the store and who's running it, and there's some online services that let you order things months in advance.

745
00:54:45,220 --> 00:54:48,096
Scott: And usually when you order things in advance, you get like a 40% discount.

746
00:54:49,800 --> 00:54:55,240
Scott: Because, you know, if a store-- like a video game store is the perfect example of how pre-orders save them a lot of money.

747
00:54:56,060 --> 00:55:00,495
Scott: 'Cause you make a $40 video game, the video game store probably paid $35 for, $30 for.

748
00:55:02,780 --> 00:55:06,180
Scott: So if they buy five of them and sell one, they lose money.

749
00:55:06,560 --> 00:55:15,240
Scott: They really have-- they want to buy exactly the number they're going to sell, or maybe one more than the number they're going to sell ever, to make the most money.

750
00:55:16,382 --> 00:55:21,079
Scott: So when they get pre-orders, they know that's a guaranteed sell, that they can buy that many copies.

751
00:55:21,860 --> 00:55:22,927
Scott: And a comic book store can't--.

